# Cline Rules — Automated Vendor Assessment Framework (PoC)

## Project Overview

This is a full-stack PoC for Carlsberg to automate AI startup vendor vetting and risk scoring across 8 compliance dimensions. It reduces time-to-onboard and produces structured, actionable reports.

**Hackathon challenge:** Build an MCP server that empowers AI agents to deliver reliable production-ready enterprise software faster. This project achieves this by exposing the entire vendor assessment workflow as MCP tools — enabling an AI agent to orchestrate vendor vetting end-to-end without human UI interaction.

---

## Tech Stack

### MCP Server (Primary Innovation Layer)

- **Language:** TypeScript (Node.js 20+)
- **SDK:** `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` (official MCP SDK)
- **Transport:** stdio (for Cline/Claude Desktop) + HTTP (for programmatic use)
- **Purpose:** Exposes all vendor assessment capabilities as MCP tools and resources
- **Communicates with:** FastAPI backend via HTTP REST calls

### Backend

- **Language:** Python 3.11+
- **Framework:** FastAPI (async-native, not Django)
- **ORM:** SQLAlchemy (async) with Alembic for migrations
- **Validation:** Pydantic v2 schemas
- **PDF Generation:** WeasyPrint (pure Python, no Chromium/Puppeteer)
- **LLM:** OpenRouter API (free-tier models: `meta-llama/llama-3-8b-instruct:free`, Mistral, Gemma) — NOT local Ollama
- **Auth:** JWT (HS256), short-lived access token (15 min) + refresh token (7 days)
- **Email:** Mailhog SMTP (PoC only, not production SMTP)

### Frontend

- **Framework:** React 18 + Vite + TypeScript
- **State Management:** React Query (server state), no Redux
- **Forms:** React Hook Form + Zod (validation)
- **UI Components:** shadcn/ui (Tailwind-based)
- **Charts:** Recharts

### Infrastructure

- **Database:** PostgreSQL 16 (Docker volume)
- **Container Orchestration:** Docker Compose
- **Reverse Proxy:** Nginx (port 80 → routes `/` to React port 3000, `/api/*` to FastAPI port 8000)
- **Dev Email:** Mailhog (SMTP port 1025, UI port 8025)

---

## Project Structure Conventions

```
vendor-assessment-poc/
├── mcp-server/             # MCP server — AI agent interface (PRIMARY INNOVATION)
│   └── src/
│       ├── index.ts        # MCP server entry point (stdio transport)
│       ├── client.ts       # HTTP client to FastAPI backend
│       ├── tools/          # One file per MCP tool
│       └── resources/      # MCP resource definitions
├── backend/
│   └── app/
│       ├── api/            # Route handlers ONLY (thin controllers)
│       ├── services/       # Business logic (vendor, scoring, report, task, notify)
│       ├── scoring/        # One scorer per dimension + base class
│       ├── models/         # SQLAlchemy ORM models
│       ├── schemas/        # Pydantic request/response schemas
│       └── core/           # Config, database engine, security helpers
├── frontend/
│   └── src/
│       ├── pages/          # One file per page/route
│       ├── components/     # Reusable UI components
│       └── api/            # API client functions (React Query hooks)
├── nginx/
│   └── nginx.conf
└── docs/                   # Architecture, phase docs, criteria
```

### MCP Server Conventions

- All tools live in `mcp-server/src/tools/<tool-name>.ts`
- All resources live in `mcp-server/src/resources/<resource-name>.ts`
- Use `zod` for input schema validation on every tool
- The MCP server authenticates to FastAPI using a service account JWT stored in `MCP_SERVICE_TOKEN` env var
- Never expose raw DB or internal errors in tool responses — return user-friendly messages
- Each tool must have a clear `description` and `inputSchema` for discoverability

### Backend Conventions

- Route handlers in `api/` should be thin — delegate all logic to `services/`
- Each SQLAlchemy model lives in `models/<entity>.py`
- Each Pydantic schema lives in `schemas/<entity>.py`
- Use async SQLAlchemy sessions throughout
- All config from environment variables via `core/config.py` (Settings class with pydantic-settings)
- **No secrets or hardcoded credentials in source code**

### Frontend Conventions

- Pages live in `src/pages/`, components in `src/components/`
- API calls are wrapped in React Query hooks inside `src/api/`
- Use shadcn/ui components first before writing custom ones
- TypeScript strict mode — no `any` types

